Hypothesis and Predictions

The analysis performed on this dataset looks at four different questions. The first question studied is whether gender has an impact upon the amount an individual spends on Valentineâs day gifts. Similarly to the first question, the second question looks into whether age has an impact upon the amount an individual spends on Valentineâs day gifts. Thirdly, the analysis explores whether the celebration of Valentineâs day has changed over time. Finally, the analysis looks to examine whether the amount an individual spends on this holiday has decreased over time.

Genders Impact on Spending

Show the code 
#Cleaning/Tidying data
gifts_gender <- gifts_gender %>%
  rename(SpendingorCelebrating = `SpendingCelebrating`)

#Bar Graph for Celebrating/Spending on Valentine's Day 
ggplot(gifts_gender, aes(x = Gender, y = SpendingorCelebrating, fill = Gender)) +
  geom_col() +
  labs(x = "Gender", y = "Percent Spent/Celebrated Valentine's Day", title = "Gender vs. Spending/Celebrating Valentine's Day")

Show the code 
#Bar Graph for flowers purchased on Valentine's Day
ggplot(gifts_gender, aes(x = Gender, y = Flowers, fill = Gender)) +
  geom_col() +
  labs(x = "Gender", y = "Average percent spent on flowers", title = "Gender vs. Percent spent on flowers purchased")

Show the code 
#Bar Graph for jewelry purchased on Valentine's Day
ggplot(gifts_gender, aes(x = Gender, y = Jewelry, fill = Gender)) +
  geom_col() +
  labs(x = "Gender", y = "Average percent spent on jewelry", title = "Gender vs. Percent spent on jewelry purchased")

Show the code 
#Bar Graph for candy purchased on Valentine's Day
ggplot(gifts_gender, aes(x = Gender, y = Candy, fill = Gender)) +
  geom_col() +
  labs(x = "Gender", y = "Average percent spent on candy", title = "Gender vs. Percent spent on candy purchased")

In the graph titled Gender vs.Â Spending/Celebrating Valentineâs Day it demonstrates how, contrary to what was expected in the first hypothesis, there is no difference between genders and the amount a person spends or celebrates on Valentineâs day. As demonstrated in the graph over 20% was spent on or celebrated on Valentineâs day for both men and women. However, there are differences between genders and what specific gifts are purchased, as seen in the graph titled Gender vs.Â Percent spent on flowers purchased. When looking at the graph that was previously mentioned the data shows that the average percent spent on flowers on Valentineâs day was significantly higher for men, over 40%, than women, lower than 20%. Therefore, this means that percent of money that was spent on flowers was higher for men than women. Similarly, when looking at the average percent of money spent on jewelry, as demonstrated in the graph titled Gender vs.Â Percent spent on jewelry purchased, it once again shows that the percent of money spent on jewelry was higher for men than for women on Valentineâs day. Contrary to this though, when it comes to the average percent spent on candy purchased on Valentineâs day, as demonstrated in the graph titled Gender vs.Â Percent spent on candy purchased, it is evident that more women than men spent money on candy as gifts. Although the difference is not as significant as that of prior graphs, it is still clear that gender has an impact on the percent spent on candy on Valentineâs day.

Impact of Age on Spending

Show the code 
#Cleaning/Tidying data
gifts_age <- gifts_age %>%
  rename(SpendingorCelebrating = `SpendingCelebrating`)

#Bar Graph for Celebrating/Spending on Valentine's Day
ggplot(gifts_age, aes(x = Age, y = SpendingorCelebrating, fill = Age)) +
  geom_col() +
  labs(x = "Age", y = "Percent Spent/Celebrated Valentine's Day", title = "Age vs. Spending/Celebrating Valentine's Day")

Show the code 
#Bar Graph for flowers purchased on Valentine's Day
ggplot(gifts_age, aes(x = Age, y = Flowers, fill = Age)) +
  geom_col() +
  labs(x = "Age", y = "Average percent spent on flowers", title = "Age vs. Percent spent on flowers purchased")

Show the code 
#Bar Graph for jewelry purchased on Valentine's Day
ggplot(gifts_age, aes(x = Age, y = Jewelry, fill = Age)) +
  geom_col() +
  labs(x = "Age", y = "Average percent spent on jewelry", title = "Age vs. Percent spent on jewelry purchased")

In the graph titled Age vs.Â Spending/Celebrating Valentineâs Day it demonstrates how age does have an impact on the amount a person spends or celebrates on Valentineâs Day. This supports the second hypothesis that age does have an impact upon the amount an individual spends on Valentineâs day gifts. Contrary to what was demonstrated between gender and celebrating Valentineâs day, when looking at the bar graph titled Age vs.Â Spending/Celebrating Valentineâs day, it is apparent that as individuals get older the percent they spend or celebrate on Valentineâs day decreases. One interesting finding, though, is that when looking at the relationship between age and specific gifts purchased on Valentineâs day, the average percent spent on the gifts does not always decrease as age increases. As mentioned previously, when the relationship between gender and specific gifts purchased on Valentineâs day was analyzed the gender did affect the percent spent on specific gifts, such as flowers or jewelry. However, age does not always have an impact on the percent spent on specific gifts. For instance, when looking at the bar graph titled Age vs Percent spent on jewelry purchased, the bar graph demonstrates that the average percent of money spent on jewelry remains fairly consistent between ages 18-24 and 25-34. On the other hand, though, when looking at the bar graph titled Age vs Percent spent on flowers purchased, the data demonstrates that ages 18-24 had the highest average percent spent on flowers. Following ages 18-24, as people increased in age the average percent spent on flowers gradually decreased. Therefore, when it comes to looking at the relationship between age and the percent spent on specific gifts it dooes not show the same distinct inverse relationship as that between age and the percent a person spends or celebrates on Valentineâs day.

Impact of Time on Valentineâs Day Celebration

Show the code 
#Bar Graph for Percent Celebrating on Valentine's Day 
ggplot(historical_spending, aes(x = Year, y = PercentCelebrating, fill = Year)) +
  geom_col() +
  labs(x = "Year", y = "Percent Celebrating", title = "Year vs. Percent of People Celebrating Valentine's Day")

The graph above titled Year vs.Â Percent of People Celebrating Valentineâs day supports the third hypothesis. This bar graph demonstrates that over time the percent of individuals celebrating Valentineâs day has gradually decreased. Although the change over the years is not too significant, it is still evident from looking at the graph that the percent is lower. For instance, when looking at the year 2012, where the percent celebrating is close to 60%, compared to the year 2020, where the percent celebrating is much further from the 60% line, there is a significant difference.

Impact of Time on Individual Spending

Show the code 
#Line Graph for Individual Spending on Valentine's Day
ggplot(historical_spending, aes(x = Year, y = PerPerson)) +
  geom_line(color = "red") +
  labs(x = "Year", y = "Average Amount spent per person", title = "Historical Spending Per Person Over Time on Valentine's Day")

Lastly, in the graph above titled Historical Spending Per Person Over Time on Valentineâs day, the results contradict the final hypothesis of the analysis. Contrary to what was expected, the line graph demonstrates that the average amount an individual spends on the holiday has increased, not decreased, over time. Although there are a couple outliers in the data where dips occur on the graph, specifically around the years 2017, 2018, 2021 and 2022, the general trend in the data is that as time has gone by people have begun to spend more money on Valentineâs day.

Conclusion

In conclusion, after performing analysis on this dataset it can be concluded that age does have an impact upon the percent of spending or celebrating on Valentineâs day. Contrary to age though, gender does not have an impact upon the percent of spending or celebrating on Valentineâs day. However, gender does have an impact upon the amount spent on specific gift, such as candy or flowers, on Valentineâs day. Furthermore, analysis of the data has demonstrated that from 2010 to present the percent of people celebrating Valentineâs day is gradually decreasing. Lastly, the analysis has demonstrated that, despite less people celebrating the holiday, over time the average amount of money spent per person on Valentineâs day has increased.
